Here's an example of code that implements a modal fake chat history using JavaScript and HTML:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Fake Chat History</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Chat History</h1>
    <div id="chat-history"></div>
    <button type="button" onclick="showChatHistory()">Show Chat History</button>
    <script>
      function showChatHistory() {
        var chatHistory = ["Message from bot 1", "Message from human 1", "Message from bot 2", "Message from human 2"];
        var chatHistoryElement = document.getElementById("chat-history");
        chatHistoryElement.innerHTML = "";
        for (var i = 0; i < chatHistory.length; i++) {
          var message = chatHistory[i];
          var messageElement = document.createElement("div");
          messageElement.className = "message";
          if (i % 2 === 0) {
            messageElement.dataset.sender = "bot";
          } else {
            messageElement.dataset.sender = "human";
          }
          messageElement.innerHTML = message;
          chatHistoryElement.appendChild(messageElement);
        }
        chatHistoryElement.style.display = "flex";
      }
    </script>
  </body>
</html>```

This code defines a button that triggers the display of a modal chat history when clicked. The chat history consists of four messages, two from a bot and two from a human. The messages are stored in an array and inserted into the DOM as div elements with classes "message". The class "message" is used to style the messages using CSS. The dataset property is used to store information about the sender of each message. The modality of the chat history is achieved by setting the display property of the container element to "flex" when the button is clicked.

There are multiple ways to achieve this in TypeScript. Here are a few options:

1. Use a union type: You can use a union type to specify that a variable or parameter can have one of several types. For example:
```typescript
type User = { name: string } | { age: number };
```
In this case, the User type can either be an object with a name property of type string, or an object with an age property of type number.

2. Use a mapped type: If you know that the shape of an object will always be the same but the properties may differ depending on the input, you can use a mapped type. Mapped types let you define a new type based on the keys and values of another type. For example:
```typescript
type Shape = { kind: "square" | "circle" };

type Square = {
  sides: number[];
};

type Circle = {
  radius: number;
};

type ShapedObject<Shape extends string> = {
  [Shape]: Shape extends "square" ? Square : Circle;
};
```
In this case, the ShapedObject type is a generic type that takes a Shape argument. The [Shape] property of the ShapedObject type is a union of Square and Circle, depending on the value of the Shape argument.

3. Assertions: Finally, you can use assertions to explicitly tell the TypeScript compiler that a value has a certain type. For example:
```javascript
const x: number = 1;

assert(typeof x === "number"); // OK

const y: string = "hello";

assert(typeof y === "string"); // Error
```

In this case, the assert statement checks that the type of the x variable is number, which is correct, whereas the second assert statement fails because the type of y is string, not number.

